[4] South Korea - WHO 4 Jun 2015
Date: Thu 4 Jun 2015
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response, Disease Outbreak News (DON) [edited]
http://www.who.int/csr/don/04-june-2015-mers-korea/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Republic of Korea
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Between [1 and 3 Jun 2015], the National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea notified WHO of 15 additional confirmed cases of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV), including 1 death.

Details of the case are as follows:

1- A 40-year-old male developed symptoms on 20 May [2015]. The patient was admitted to the same hospital as the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015]. He was admitted to another hospital between 25 and 27 May [2015]. From 28 to 30 May [2015], the patient was admitted to a 3rd hospital. As symptoms worsened, on 30 May [2015], he was transferred to a nationally designated medical centre for treatment. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015].

2- A 45-year-old male developed symptoms on 22 May [2015] and was admitted to hospital on the same day. Between 15 and 16 May [2015], the patient visited his father while he was admitted to the same ward as the 1st case. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. Currently, he is in stable condition.

3- A 77-year-old female developed symptoms on 20 May [2015]. The patient was admitted to the same ward as the 1st case from 4 to 16 May [2015]. She visited a hospital on 30 May [2015] and tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

4- A 60-year-old male developed symptoms on 28 May [2015]. From 16 to 17 May [2015], the patient cared for a family member who was admitted to the same hospital as the 1st case. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

5- A 40-year-old male developed symptoms on 23 May [2015]. The patient was admitted to the same ward as the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015]. He was transferred to a nationally designated medical centre. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. Currently, he is in stable condition.

6- A 59-year-old female developed symptoms on 23 May [2015], which disappeared on 29 May [2015]. As symptoms returned, the patient was admitted to a nationally designated medical centre. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. The patient cared for her husband who was admitted to the same hospital as the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015]. Currently, she is in stable condition.

7- A 39-year-old female developed fever on 27 May [2015]. The patient cared for her son who was admitted to the same hospital as the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015]. She was later admitted to the nationally designated medical center. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on 31 May [2015]. Currently, she is in stable condition.

8- A 73-year-old male developed symptoms on 31 May [2015] while admitted to hospital for unrelated medical conditions since 27 May [2015]. The patient, who has comorbidities, shared the room with a MERS-CoV laboratory-confirmed case (case n. 1 -- see above) between 28 and 30 May [2015]. Once he tested positive for MERS-CoV on [1 Jun 2015], the patient was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre.

9- A 78-year-old male developed symptoms on 31 May [2015] while admitted to hospital for unrelated medical conditions. The patient, who has comorbidities, shared the room with a MERS-CoV laboratory-confirmed case (case n. 1 -- see above) between 28 and 30 May [2015]. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on [1 Jun 2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

10- A 57-year-old female was hospitalized in the same ward with the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015]. The patient, who had comorbidities, was admitted to ICU. She passed away on [1 Jun 2015].

11- A 43-year-old male developed symptoms on 21 May [2015] and was admitted to hospital on 28 May [2015]. Between 13 and 18 May [2015], the patient visited his son while he was admitted to the same ward as the 1st case. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on [2 Jun 2015]. Currently, he is in stable condition.

12- A 55-year-old male developed symptoms on [1 Jun 2015]. The patient, who has comorbidities, was admitted to the same ward as the 1st case from 4 to 28 May [2015]. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on [2 Jun 2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

13- A 58-year-old male developed symptoms on 29 May [2015]. From 15 to 17 May [2015], He visited his wife while she was admitted to the same room as the 1st case. The patient, who has comorbidities, tested positive for MERS-CoV on [2 Jun 2015]. Currently, he is in stable condition.

14- A 77-year-old female tested positive for MERS-CoV on [2 Jun 2015]. The patient was admitted to hospital on [25 Apr 2015] due to an unrelated medical condition. She shared the same ward as the 1st case from 15 to 17 May [2015].

15- A 60-year-old male developed symptoms on 30 May [2015] while admitted to hospital for an unrelated medical condition since 22 May [2015]. The patient shared the same room as a MERS-CoV laboratory-confirmed case (case n. 1 -- see above) from 25 to 27 May [2015]. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on [2 Jun 2015].

Contact tracing of household and healthcare contacts is ongoing for the cases.

The National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea also notified WHO of the death of 1 previously reported MERS-CoV cases. The case was reported in a previous DON on 30 May [2015] (case n. 6).

So far, a total of 30 MERS-CoV cases, including 2 deaths, have been reported to WHO by the National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea. One of the 30 cases is the case that was confirmed in China and also notified by the National IHR Focal Point of China.

Globally, since September 2012, WHO has been notified of 1179 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 442 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[Of the 15 cases described in the above WHO report, 12 were secondary cases (2nd generation) having had contact with the hospital where the index case was during the period 15-17 May 2015. The remaining 3 were tertiary cases (3rd generation) having had contact with case no. 1 in the above WHO report (case no. 16 in the South Korean MOH line listing of cases).

Of note, as of the current WHO update including the 9 cases in Saudi Arabia reported by WHO today (see section [6] below], there have now been 1179 laboratory-confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection including at least 442 related deaths reported. - Mod.MPP]

